{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507578"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2643"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.21,0.22,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2643"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40432"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2457"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman underwent an elective total hysterectomy under general anaesthesia. The procedure was longer than expected due to bleeding at the surgical site. The surgeon closed up 20 minutes ago. The patient received propofol, cisatricurium, sevoflurane, fentanyl, and droperidol intra-operatively. She has been extubated but appears to have an abdominal breathing pattern and her PaCO2 on an arterial blood gas is 55mmHg. A peripheral neuro-stimulatory test is performed, which indicates residual shallow neuromuscular blockade.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments should be given?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neostigmine and glycopyrrolate","Neostigmine alone","Sugammadex","Succinylcholine","Glycopyrrolate alone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has received cisatracurium, a non-depolarising neuromuscular blocking agent which works by competitively binding to acetylcholine (ACh) receptors on the post-synaptic membrane. This does not cause depolarisation but rather prevents ACh from binding at the neuromuscular junction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeostigmine\u003C/strong\u003E is an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor that interferes with the breakdown of ACh both in the neuromuscular junction and systemically. This increases the amount of ACh within the neuromuscular junction overcoming the inhibition by cisatracurium. Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors are used in the reversal of shallow and moderate levels of neuromuscular blockade. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtropine or \u003Cstrong\u003Eglycopyrrolate\u003C/strong\u003E are anti-muscarinic agents which should be administered concurrently with neostigmine to prevent the unwanted side effects of increasing systemic ACh concentration including bradycardia, salivation, and increased bowel peristalsis. However, when used alone, they will not reverse the patient\u0027s residual paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESugammadex\u003C/strong\u003E is a chelating agent that works by binding directly with molecules of rocuronium or vecuronium and thus inhibiting these agents from binding to the post-synaptic ACh receptor. Whilst it is indeed used to reverse residual paralysis, it is specific to rocuronium and vecuronium - it will therefore have no effect on paralysis from other agents such as cisatracurium, atracurium and suxamethonium. This is in contrast to neostigmine which acts indirectly by increasing ACh levels. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuccinylcholine\u003C/strong\u003E (suxamethonium) is a depolarising neuromuscular blocking agent that works by binding to post-synaptic nicotinic receptors and acting like ACh by inducing depolarisation. It is an analogue of ACh. This is manifested by skeletal muscle fasciculations, with paralysis following due to \u201cdesensitisation\u201d of receptors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For reversal of shallow and moderate neuromuscular blockade, neostigmine should be used concurrently with glycopyrrolate.","Glycopyrrolate should be administered concurrently with neostigmine to prevent the unwanted side effects of bradycardia, salivation, and increased bowel peristalsis.","Sugammadex is a reversal agent which is specific to rocuronium and vecuronium and will not have any effect on paralysis from other agents."],"references":["Amorim P, Lagarto F, Gomes B, Esteves S, Bismarck J, Rodrigues N, et al. Neostigmine vs. sugammadex: observational cohort study comparing the quality of recovery using the Postoperative Quality Recovery Scale. Acta Anaesthesiol Scand. 2014;58(9):1101-10.","Hristovska AM, Duch P, Allingstrup M, Afshari A. Efficacy and safety of sugammadex versus neostigmine in reversing neuromuscular blockade in adults. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2017;8(8):Cd012763.","Lee YJ, Oh AY, Koo BW, Han JW, Park JH, Hong JP, et al. Postoperative residual neuromuscular blockade after reversal based on a qualitative peripheral nerve stimulator response: A randomised controlled trial. Eur J Anaesthesiol. 2020;37(3):196-202.","Tajaate N, Schreiber JU, Fuchs-Buder T, Jelting Y, Kranke P. Neostigmine-based reversal of intermediate acting neuromuscular blocking agents to prevent postoperative residual paralysis: A systematic review. Eur J Anaesthesiol. 2018;35(3):184-92."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40432"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40432"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-11T13:13:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-11T13:14:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2643"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"